    "summary": "Against \"character\" -- too ambiguous without modifier",
    "content": "**Strongest objection to \"character\":** It is ambiguous in exactly the wrong way. When the reader encounters \"all things have their character,\" the most natural English reading is personality or temperament -- a descriptive property that a thing *happens to have*. But the author's 德 is constitutive -- what *makes* a thing what it is. \"Character\" does not carry that constitutive force without a modifier. \"Defining character\" or \"constitutive nature\" both fix this; bare \"character\" does not.\n"
